    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-05-12T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-05-12T05:00:00-05:00" n="577"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d577">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.42700(R)/5–1248: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Durbrow</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-05-12T13:00:00+03:00"
                            >May 12, 1948—1 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>887. Reply of Foreign Office to Embassy request for determination source
                    interference American stations on 9750, 11730, 15130, 15250 KC (<gloss
                        target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 807 and despatch 391 April 30<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d577fn1">Despatch No. 391 not found in Department of State
                        files.</note>) consists repetition statement Soviet stations not using those
                    frequencies. Copy note by airmail.<note n="2" xml:id="d577fn2">The Foreign
                        Ministry’s note No. 71 of May 8, 1948, was transmitted in despatch No. 418
                        from Moscow on May 13, not printed. The note stated that these frequencies
                        were not used by radio stations in the Soviet Union, as had already been
                        indicated in notes No. 45 of April 12, and No. 54 of April 19, neither
                        printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>For reasons stated ref <gloss target="#t_desp1">desp</gloss> recommend no further
                    protest Soviet Government but employment whatever technical means available
                    avoid jamming with brief statement (if we are confident that such is case) that
                    programs experiencing artificial interference and that listeners should search
                    within certain wave lengths, for program which will continue be presented usual
                    time.</p>
                <p>Department pass Vladivostok 70.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Durbrow</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
